### ❹ Assertion Roulette — Medium

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org Extended Catalog — Assertion Roulette
**Location:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35–38)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
```

**Why it's a problem:** 4 assertions with no message parameters. When one fails, the MSTest output says `Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<Alice>. Actual:<null>.` — you must open the source to figure out *which property* was wrong. Per Peruma et al. (CASCON 2019), this is the most prevalent smell in open-source projects.

**Integration-test calibration:** Stays Medium — this is a readability/diagnostics issue regardless of scope.

**Fix:** Add message parameters to each assertion:

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert.");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should match inserted value.");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should match inserted value.");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Persisted user should have a positive database ID.");
```

